      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Timing · Article 5 of 5</span>
        <h1>PPS Output and Disciplined Oscillators</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          The pulse-per-second (PPS) signal is how a GNSS receiver delivers precise time
          to external equipment — a hardware pulse whose rising edge is synchronised to
          GPS time with nanosecond accuracy. Understanding PPS, its limitations, and how
          GPS-disciplined oscillators extend its usefulness is essential for anyone building
          timing infrastructure.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>8 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#what-is-pps">What is a PPS signal?</a></li>
          <li><a href="#hardware">Hardware interface</a></li>
          <li><a href="#accuracy">PPS accuracy and error sources</a></li>
          <li><a href="#gpsdo">GPS-disciplined oscillators (GPSDO)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#holdover">Holdover behaviour</a></li>
          <li><a href="#using-pps">Using PPS in practice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="what-is-pps">What is a PPS signal?</h2>
      <p>
        A <strong>Pulse Per Second (PPS)</strong> signal is a periodic electrical pulse
        output by a GNSS receiver or timing device. The rising edge of each pulse is
        precisely synchronised to GNSS time — typically GPS time or UTC — with nanosecond
        accuracy. The pulse width is usually 100 ms or 500 ms, but the timing reference
        point is always the <strong>rising edge</strong>.
      </p>

      <!-- PPS waveform diagram -->
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-label">PPS signal — rising edge aligned to GPS second</div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 160" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <!-- Time axis -->
          <line x1="40" y1="120" x2="640" y2="120" stroke="var(--border)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
          <!-- Second markers -->
          <line x1="100" y1="115" x2="100" y2="125" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
          <text x="100" y="138" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">t=0 s</text>
          <line x1="280" y1="115" x2="280" y2="125" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
          <text x="280" y="138" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">t=1 s</text>
          <line x1="460" y1="115" x2="460" y2="125" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
          <text x="460" y="138" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">t=2 s</text>
          <line x1="640" y1="115" x2="640" y2="125" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
          <text x="640" y="138" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">t=3 s</text>
          <!-- Pulse 1 -->
          <polyline points="100,120 100,30 190,30 190,120" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="2"/>
          <!-- Pulse 2 -->
          <polyline points="280,120 280,30 370,30 370,120" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="2"/>
          <!-- Pulse 3 -->
          <polyline points="460,120 460,30 550,30 550,120" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="2"/>
          <!-- Rising edge annotation -->
          <line x1="100" y1="30" x2="100" y2="10" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="0.8" stroke-dasharray="3 2"/>
          <text x="104" y="18" font-size="10" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--mono)">Rising edge = GPS second boundary</text>
          <!-- Pulse width annotation -->
          <line x1="100" y1="50" x2="190" y2="50" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.5" stroke-dasharray="3 2"/>
          <line x1="100" y1="44" x2="100" y2="56" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <line x1="190" y1="44" x2="190" y2="56" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <text x="145" y="46" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">pulse width</text>
          <text x="145" y="58" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">(100 ms typical)</text>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <p>
        A companion message — typically an NMEA <code>$GPRMC</code> or
        <code>$GPZDA</code> sentence — is transmitted over serial at the same time
        as each pulse, providing the calendar time (year, month, day, hour, minute, second)
        that the pulse represents. The PPS pulse marks <em>when</em> the second occurs;
        the serial message tells the system <em>which</em> second it is.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>UTC vs GPS PPS:</strong> Most timing receivers can output PPS aligned to
          either GPS time or UTC. The difference is the current leap second offset (18 seconds
          as of 2024). For applications requiring UTC-aligned timestamps (MiFID II compliance,
          NTP servers), always configure the receiver to output UTC PPS and verify that the
          receiver knows the current leap second count.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="hardware">Hardware interface</h2>
      <p>
        PPS is a simple digital signal. The electrical specifications vary by receiver and
        application, but the most common standards are:
      </p>

      <div class="hw-table">
        <div class="hw-row hw-header">
          <span>Standard</span>
          <span>Voltage levels</span>
          <span>Impedance</span>
          <span>Typical use</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hw-row">
          <span><strong>TTL</strong></span>
          <span>0 V / 3.3–5 V</span>
          <span>50 Ω (driven)</span>
          <span>Embedded systems, microcontrollers, u-blox modules</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hw-row">
          <span><strong>CMOS</strong></span>
          <span>0 V / 3.3 V</span>
          <span>High impedance</span>
          <span>Modern low-power receiver modules</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hw-row">
          <span><strong>RS-232</strong></span>
          <span>±5 V / ±12 V</span>
          <span>3–7 kΩ</span>
          <span>Legacy serial port PPS on DB9 pin 1 (DCD)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hw-row">
          <span><strong>BNC / SMA (50 Ω)</strong></span>
          <span>0 V / 5 V (into 50 Ω)</span>
          <span>50 Ω</span>
          <span>Lab instruments, frequency standards, timing receivers</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hw-row">
          <span><strong>Differential (RS-422)</strong></span>
          <span>±3.5 V differential</span>
          <span>100 Ω differential</span>
          <span>Long cable runs, noise-sensitive environments</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        When interfacing PPS to a Linux system, use a GPIO pin or the serial port DCD
        line with the <code>pps-gpio</code> or <code>pps-ldisc</code> kernel driver.
        These drivers timestamp the PPS rising edge using the kernel's hardware clock
        interrupt — giving sub-microsecond accuracy. The <code>gpsd</code> daemon then
        makes PPS available to <code>ntpd</code> or <code>chrony</code> as a precision
        time reference.
      </p>

      <div class="linux-setup">
        <div class="ls-title">Linux PPS setup — typical stack</div>
        <div class="ls-chain">
          <div class="ls-node">
            <div class="ls-name">GNSS receiver</div>
            <div class="ls-detail">PPS on GPIO pin · NMEA on UART</div>
          </div>
          <div class="ls-arrow">↓</div>
          <div class="ls-node">
            <div class="ls-name">pps-gpio kernel driver</div>
            <div class="ls-detail">Timestamps PPS edge with hardware interrupt</div>
          </div>
          <div class="ls-arrow">↓</div>
          <div class="ls-node">
            <div class="ls-name">gpsd</div>
            <div class="ls-detail">Parses NMEA · exposes PPS via shared memory (SHM)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="ls-arrow">↓</div>
          <div class="ls-node ls-highlight">
            <div class="ls-name">chrony / ntpd</div>
            <div class="ls-detail">Uses PPS as precision reference · serves NTP to local network</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="accuracy">PPS accuracy and error sources</h2>
      <p>
        The PPS signal itself is not the only source of timing error. Several effects
        degrade the accuracy between GPS time and the ultimate timestamp in an application:
      </p>

      <div class="error-chain">
        <div class="ec-row">
          <div class="ec-source">Satellite clock error</div>
          <div class="ec-budget">~5–10 ns (broadcast)</div>
          <div class="ec-bar"><div class="ec-fill" style="width:30%; background:rgba(251,191,36,0.5);"></div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="ec-row">
          <div class="ec-source">Ionospheric delay (L1)</div>
          <div class="ec-budget">~1–5 ns (modelled)</div>
          <div class="ec-bar"><div class="ec-fill" style="width:20%; background:rgba(255,71,87,0.4);"></div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="ec-row">
          <div class="ec-source">Antenna cable delay</div>
          <div class="ec-budget">~5 ns/m (must calibrate)</div>
          <div class="ec-bar"><div class="ec-fill" style="width:25%; background:rgba(240,165,0,0.4);"></div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="ec-row">
          <div class="ec-source">Receiver internal delay</div>
          <div class="ec-budget">~10–50 ns (calibrated in firmware)</div>
          <div class="ec-bar"><div class="ec-fill" style="width:35%; background:rgba(163,230,53,0.4);"></div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="ec-row">
          <div class="ec-source">PPS output jitter</div>
          <div class="ec-budget">~1–10 ns (hardware quality dependent)</div>
          <div class="ec-bar"><div class="ec-fill" style="width:15%; background:rgba(0,212,170,0.5);"></div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="ec-row">
          <div class="ec-source">OS interrupt latency (software timestamp)</div>
          <div class="ec-budget">~1–10 µs (varies by OS load)</div>
          <div class="ec-bar"><div class="ec-fill" style="width:80%; background:rgba(255,71,87,0.6);"></div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="ec-total">Hardware PPS timestamp: ~20–50 ns total · Software timestamp: ~1–10 µs</div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Cable delay is the most commonly overlooked error:</strong> Coaxial cable
          propagates signals at approximately 2×10⁸ m/s (66% of the speed of light for
          typical RG-58). A 10-metre cable introduces ~50 ns of delay. For timing better
          than 100 ns, measure your cable delay and enter it as a calibration offset in
          the receiver's timing configuration. Many receivers have a dedicated
          "antenna cable delay" or "cable compensation" setting for exactly this purpose.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="gpsdo">GPS-disciplined oscillators (GPSDO)</h2>
      <p>
        A standalone GNSS receiver outputs PPS only when tracking satellites. The moment
        the antenna is obstructed — briefly by a passing lorry, longer by a power outage
        — PPS output may stop or degrade. Critical infrastructure needs continuous,
        uninterrupted timing.
      </p>
      <p>
        A <strong>GPS-Disciplined Oscillator (GPSDO)</strong> solves this by combining
        a GNSS receiver with a high-quality local oscillator (OCXO or rubidium) in a
        phase-locked loop:
      </p>

      <div class="gpsdo-diagram">
        <div class="gd-block gd-gps">
          <div class="gd-title">GNSS receiver</div>
          <div class="gd-detail">Produces PPS when satellites available. Provides long-term frequency reference.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="gd-arrow">→ phase error →</div>
        <div class="gd-block gd-loop">
          <div class="gd-title">Phase comparator + loop filter</div>
          <div class="gd-detail">Measures phase difference between GNSS PPS and oscillator output. Generates correction voltage. Long time constant (minutes to hours) for stability.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="gd-arrow">→ EFC →</div>
        <div class="gd-block gd-osc">
          <div class="gd-title">Oscillator (OCXO / Rb)</div>
          <div class="gd-detail">Electronically frequency-controlled (EFC). Provides short-term stability, low phase noise. Free-runs during GNSS outages.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="gd-output">
          <div class="gd-out-item">PPS output (continuous)</div>
          <div class="gd-out-item">10 MHz reference signal</div>
          <div class="gd-out-item">NMEA / timing messages</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The GNSS signal provides <strong>long-term accuracy</strong> — it keeps the oscillator
        on frequency over hours and days. The local oscillator provides
        <strong>short-term stability</strong> — low phase noise, continuous output and immunity
        to brief GNSS outages. Together they achieve better performance than either alone.
      </p>

      <div class="gpsdo-types">
        <div class="gt-card">
          <div class="gt-osc">OCXO-based GPSDO</div>
          <div class="gt-accuracy">~10–30 ns steady-state</div>
          <div class="gt-holdover">Holdover: ~1 µs/hour drift</div>
          <div class="gt-cost">£200–£2,000</div>
          <div class="gt-use">NTP servers, telecom small cells, test equipment reference</div>
        </div>
        <div class="gt-card gt-rb">
          <div class="gt-osc">Rubidium GPSDO</div>
          <div class="gt-accuracy">~5–15 ns steady-state</div>
          <div class="gt-holdover">Holdover: ~0.1 µs/hour drift</div>
          <div class="gt-cost">£1,000–£10,000</div>
          <div class="gt-use">Telecom grandmaster clocks, power grid PMUs, financial trading, 5G synchronisation</div>
        </div>
        <div class="gt-card gt-cs">
          <div class="gt-osc">Caesium GPSDO</div>
          <div class="gt-accuracy">~1–5 ns steady-state</div>
          <div class="gt-holdover">Holdover: ~0.01 µs/hour drift</div>
          <div class="gt-cost">£10,000–£50,000+</div>
          <div class="gt-use">National metrology, VLBI stations, master timing infrastructure</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="holdover">Holdover behaviour</h2>
      <p>
        When GNSS signals are lost, the GPSDO enters <strong>holdover mode</strong> —
        the oscillator free-runs using its last frequency correction from the GPS-steering
        loop. The frequency estimate degrades over time as temperature and aging effects
        push the oscillator away from its corrected value.
      </p>
      <p>
        The time error during holdover grows approximately as:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">Δt_holdover(T) ≈ ½ · (df/dt) · T²</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          df/dt = oscillator frequency aging rate (fractional frequency per second)<br/>
          T = time since GNSS loss (seconds)<br/><br/>
          For a rubidium oscillator with aging rate 10⁻¹³/s:
          After 1 hour (T = 3600 s): Δt = ½ × 10⁻¹³ × 3600² ≈ 0.65 ns — negligible.<br/>
          After 1 day (T = 86400 s): Δt = ½ × 10⁻¹³ × 86400² ≈ 374 ns — still &lt;1 µs.<br/><br/>
          In practice, initial frequency uncertainty after GNSS loss dominates the early
          holdover error — the oscillator frequency is known only to the precision of the
          GPS steering loop (~10⁻¹² or better for a well-designed GPSDO).
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="using-pps">Using PPS in practice</h2>
      <p>
        Key practical considerations when deploying PPS-based timing:
      </p>

      <div class="practical-list">
        <div class="prac-item">
          <div class="prac-title">Always use hardware timestamping</div>
          <div class="prac-desc">
            Software-timestamped PPS (relying on the OS scheduler to record the interrupt time)
            introduces 1–100 µs of jitter — completely negating the nanosecond accuracy of the
            GNSS receiver. Use hardware PPS drivers (pps-gpio on Linux, dedicated hardware
            timestamping NICs for network PTP) that capture the edge with a hardware counter.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="prac-item">
          <div class="prac-title">Calibrate cable delay</div>
          <div class="prac-desc">
            Measure or calculate the antenna cable propagation delay (~5 ns/m for RG-58, ~4 ns/m
            for LMR-400). Enter this value in the receiver's cable delay compensation field.
            For lab-grade timing, use a TDR (Time Domain Reflectometer) to measure the actual
            delay rather than estimating from cable specs.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="prac-item">
          <div class="prac-title">Verify UTC alignment</div>
          <div class="prac-desc">
            Confirm that the receiver is outputting UTC PPS (not GPS PPS) if UTC-traceable
            timestamps are required. Check the leap second count in the NMEA ZDA sentence or
            receiver status. After a leap second insertion, some receivers take several minutes
            to update — monitor for 1-second timestamp jumps after known leap second events.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="prac-item">
          <div class="prac-title">Monitor antenna health</div>
          <div class="prac-desc">
            PPS accuracy degrades silently when satellite count drops (multipath, jamming, obstruction).
            Monitor satellite count and C/N₀ continuously. Configure alerts for drops below 4 satellites
            or loss of PPS lock. For critical systems, use a multi-constellation receiver with
            antenna monitoring (RAIM or dual-antenna) to detect anomalies before they affect timing.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="prac-item">
          <div class="prac-title">Define your holdover budget</div>
          <div class="prac-desc">
            Before deploying a timing system, calculate the required holdover duration for your
            application's worst-case GNSS outage scenario. Match the oscillator grade to this
            budget. A telecoms grandmaster serving 5G base stations (±130 ns requirement) needs
            a rubidium oscillator to hold over more than ~15 minutes — an OCXO is marginal.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section complete -->
      <div class="section-complete">
        <div class="complete-icon">✅</div>
        <div>
          <div class="complete-title">Timing section complete</div>
          <div class="complete-body">
            You now understand GNSS as a timing infrastructure — from the atomic clocks
            in orbit to the PPS pulse on your receiver's GPIO pin, and the disciplined
            oscillators that keep critical systems running through outages.
            The Learn section is now complete.
          </div>
          <a href="/learn" class="complete-link">Back to Learn →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⚡</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Rising edge is the reference</div>
          <div class="summary-body">PPS accuracy lives in the rising edge — not the pulse width. The companion NMEA sentence identifies which second. Always use hardware timestamping to capture the edge.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📏</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Cable delay matters</div>
          <div class="summary-body">~5 ns/m for RG-58. A 10 m antenna cable introduces 50 ns of delay. Measure it and enter it in the receiver's cable compensation setting — this is the most commonly missed calibration.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔒</div>
          <div class="summary-title">GPSDO for continuous timing</div>
          <div class="summary-body">GNSS + high-quality oscillator in a phase-locked loop. GPS provides long-term accuracy; the oscillator provides short-term stability and holdover. Rubidium GPSDOs are the standard for critical infrastructure.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔋</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Size your holdover budget</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Calculate worst-case outage duration × required accuracy → choose oscillator grade. OCXO: ~1 µs/hour. Rubidium: ~0.1 µs/hour. Match the oscillator to the application requirement.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/timing/clock-error" class="nav-prev">← Clock Error</a>
        <a href="/learn" class="nav-next">Back to Learn →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Lombardi, M. A. (2008). The use of GPS disciplined oscillators as primary frequency standards for calibration and metrology laboratories. <em>NCSLI Measure</em>, 3(3), 56–65.</li>
          <li>NIST Special Publication 960-12 — Precision Measurement of Cable and Antenna Delays. <a href="https://www.nist.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">nist.gov →</a></li>
          <li>u-blox Application Note — Timing. <a href="https://www.u-blox.com/en/technologies/timing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">u-blox →</a></li>
          <li>Symmetricom — GPS Disciplined Oscillator Application Guide.</li>
          <li>RFC 7822 — Network Time Protocol Best Current Practice. <a href="https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7822" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">rfc-editor.org →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

